# =============================================================================
# threshold-router SKILL.md Example
# =============================================================================
# LOCATION: ~/.claude/skills/threshold-router/SKILL.md
#
# PURPOSE:  This is the skill definition file for the threshold router.
#           Claude Code reads this file when the skill is invoked and follows
#           the instructions to score complexity and assign a tier.
#
# HOW SKILLS WORK:
#   Skills are markdown files with YAML frontmatter. The frontmatter tells
#   Claude Code the skill's name and description. The markdown body contains
#   the instructions Claude follows when the skill is invoked.
#
#   Skills live in ~/.claude/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md
#   They are invoked with: /skill-name (in the Claude Code prompt)
#   Or automatically if referenced in CLAUDE.md
#
# CUSTOMIZATION:
#   - Add scoring signals relevant to your domain
#   - Adjust tier thresholds (maybe T2 starts at 5 for your team)
#   - Add override keywords your team uses
#   - Modify tier behaviors to match your review tools
# =============================================================================

---
name: threshold-router
description: >
  Mandatory complexity scoring system. Computes a 0-10+ score for every
  prompt and assigns a tier (T1, T2, T3) that controls verification depth.
  Must be invoked on EVERY user prompt before any other action.
---

# Threshold Router

## Activation
# This section tells Claude when to invoke this skill.
# "MANDATORY" and "EVERY" are strong signals that Claude should
# always run this, not just when the user asks for it.
This skill is MANDATORY. Invoke it on EVERY user prompt, no exceptions.
Announce the tier at the start of every response: [T1], [T2], or [T3].

## Scoring Table

# Each signal adds to the complexity score. The total determines the tier.
# You can customize these signals for your domain. For example, if your
# team works heavily with databases, you might add more database-related
# signals.

Compute a complexity score by summing applicable signals:

| Signal                              | Score  |
|-------------------------------------|--------|
| Per 3 files mentioned or affected   | +1     |
| Destructive keywords (delete, drop) | +2     |
| Cross-system scope (API + frontend) | +2     |
| New architecture or infrastructure  | +3     |
| Security / IAM / auth changes       | +2     |
| Production deployment               | +2     |
| Ambiguous or open-ended request     | +1     |
| Database schema changes             | +2     |
| Multi-service coordination          | +2     |
| Performance-critical path           | +1     |

# CUSTOMIZATION IDEAS:
# | Your custom signal                  | +N     |
# | Involves legacy code (no tests)     | +2     |
# | Affects billing/payment logic       | +3     |
# | Changes public API contract         | +2     |
# | Modifies CI/CD pipeline             | +1     |

## Tier Assignment

# These thresholds can be adjusted. If your team is more cautious,
# lower the T2 threshold (e.g., T2 starts at 3). If you want more
# speed, raise it (e.g., T2 starts at 6).

| Tier | Score | Label            | Behavior                                |
|------|-------|------------------|-----------------------------------------|
| T1   | 0-3   | Solo             | Execute directly. Report results.       |
| T2   | 4-7   | Lean pipeline    | Execute, then spawn review subagents.   |
| T3   | 8+    | Full orchestra   | Plan (ultrathink), execute, full review.|

## Tier-Specific Behavior

### [T1] Solo (score 0-3)
# For simple tasks: typo fixes, small config changes, adding a comment.
- Proceed directly with implementation
- Run basic verification (type check, relevant tests)
- No subagent review needed

### [T2] Lean Pipeline (score 4-7)
# For medium tasks: multi-file changes, new features, bug fixes.
- Implement the change
- Spawn review subagents to check:
  - Code quality and style consistency
  - Test coverage for changed code
  - Potential bugs or regressions
- Address any findings before reporting done

### [T3] Full Orchestra (score 8+)
# For complex tasks: architectural changes, security updates, major refactors.
- Create a detailed plan using extended thinking (ultrathink)
- Get plan approval before implementing
- Implement the change
- Run full review pipeline:
  - OCR multi-agent code review (if available)
  - Codex verification (if available)
  - Type checker + full test suite
- Address all findings before reporting done

## Override System

# These keywords let users bypass the scoring system when they know
# what they want. The override applies to the CURRENT prompt only.

Users can override the computed tier with keywords:

- **"just do it"** -- Force downgrade to T1 (skip all reviews)
- **"full review"** -- Force upgrade to T3 (maximum verification)

The override applies to the current prompt only, not future prompts.

## Response Format

# This template ensures consistent tier announcements across all responses.
Always start your response with the tier announcement:

```
[T1] This is a simple change...
[T2] This involves multiple files...
[T3] This is a complex architectural change...
```

## Edge Cases

# These rules handle ambiguous situations.
- If scoring is ambiguous, round UP (prefer more review over less)
- If the user says "quick fix" but the change is complex, announce T2
  and explain why you scored it higher
- If the user provides no context, ask for clarification rather than
  defaulting to T1
